    "summary": "Menander I (reigned c. 165–130 BC) was the most successful ruler of the [[event:1104|Indo-Greek Kingdom]], whose military campaigns extended Greek power deep into the Indian subcontinent and who is remembered in Buddhist tradition as a king who converted to Buddhism after philosophical debates with the monk Nagasena.\n\nMenander expanded his kingdom from its base in Bactria into the Punjab and possibly as far as the Ganges plain, threatening the [[event:1103|Shunga Dynasty]]'s heartland. His philosophical dialogues with the monk Nagasena are recorded in the Milindapanha (Questions of Milinda), a Buddhist text in which Menander (called Milinda) asks penetrating questions about Buddhist doctrine and is ultimately persuaded of the truth of Buddhism. Whether this represents actual conversion or literary convention is debated. His coins, distributed across a vast territory, bear the epithet Soter (Savior), and after his death Buddhist tradition records that his ashes were divided among many cities — an honor normally reserved for Buddhist saints. He represents the high point of Greek-Indian cultural interaction.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menander_I",
